## Observations

- Blocking/privacy, writing/AI, language, capture, credentials, userscripts, appearance, DevTools, research, media, focus, clipping, and task workflows have strong adoption signals.
- Declarative browser-owned capabilities can materially reduce persistent background work; uBlock Origin Lite explicitly describes browser-performed filtering without a permanent extension process.
- Small, focused local tools such as JSON Formatter, Video Speed Controller, Google Dictionary, and Scholar demonstrate that high-value plug-ins do not need large packages or broad services.
- AI writing and clipping products show that page content and personal communications can cross provider boundaries; Turing must make provider data flow, retention configuration, and redaction visible.
- Credential and web3 products demonstrate severe confused-deputy, signing, spoofing, and secret-handling risk.
- Framework DevTools demonstrate demand for a public plug-in protocol that can inspect framework semantics without private engine bridges.

## Proposed first-party portfolio

The proposed initial portfolio is Turing Shield, Capture, Write, Translate & Define, Vault, Clip, Focus, Tasks, Research, Media Controls, Scripts, Framework Inspector, JSON & Data Inspector, Color & Layout Tools, and AI Agent. Web3 Bridge is optional, separately audited, disabled by default, and not a baseline capability.

The first implementation set should be smaller: Capture, Shield rule/UI package, Framework Inspector, JSON & Data Inspector, and AI Agent. Together they exercise capture, declarative network policy, DevTools, structured viewers, component/web plug-ins, permissions, store updates, resource accounting, accessibility, and agent policy.

## Architecture recommendation

Use three plug-in tiers:

1. Web-compatible plug-ins with an explicit supported WebExtensions subset.
2. Turing Component plug-ins using WIT and a resource-limited WebAssembly component runtime.
3. Separately installed, signed, out-of-process native connectors for exceptional enterprise/developer integrations.

First-party plug-ins use the same manifest, capability, lifecycle, audit, update, and resource machinery. Browser-owned security services retain network filtering, credential filling, capture permission, downloads, trusted UI, and agent authorization.

## Security and performance implications

Recent research continues to find malicious extension campaigns, generative-AI-themed malicious extensions, ordering/interference attacks, and measurable page-load or energy costs. Turing should therefore require package immutability, no remote code, minimum permissions, event-driven execution, per-plug-in process/resource attribution, review and revocation, and adversarial evaluation.

## Falsifiable experiments

- `EXP-PLUGIN-001`: Manifest V3 compatibility adapter across twenty representative API patterns.
- `EXP-PLUGIN-002`: web worker versus Wasm component versus native connector isolation and resource comparison.
- `EXP-PLUGIN-003`: first-party Capture, Shield, Framework Inspector, JSON, and AI reference implementations.
- `EXP-PLUGIN-004`: malicious package and update corpus.
- `EXP-PLUGIN-005`: install/permission/revocation usability with keyboard and screen-reader users.
- `EXP-PLUGIN-006`: disabled, idle, active, 30-tab, update, crash, and recovery resource budgets.

